```markdown
# Research: WebSocket vs SSE for Real-Time Dashboard Updates

**Bead**: ga-124
**Researcher**: tesla
**Date**: 2026-04-07
**Time spent**: ~45min

## Research Question

Should we use WebSocket or Server-Sent Events (SSE) for real-time notifications in the dashboard?

## Summary

For one-way server-to-client updates (dashboard notifications), SSE is simpler and sufficient. WebSocket is better for bidirectional communication we don't currently need. Both have good browser support.

## Detailed Findings

### Server-Sent Events (SSE)

**What it is**: HTTP-based protocol for server→client streaming over a persistent connection.

**Use cases**: Notifications, live feeds, status updates, any one-way push from server.

**Pros**:
- Simpler than WebSocket (just HTTP, no protocol upgrade)
- Auto-reconnect built-in (browser handles it)
- Works through firewalls/proxies easily
- Less overhead for one-way updates
- Native browser API (EventSource)

**Cons**:
- Only server→client (no client→server data streaming)
- Limited to text-based data (JSON is fine)
- Connection limits (6 per domain in older browsers, less of an issue with HTTP/2)

**Sources**:
- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Server-sent_events
- https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/server-sent-events.html

### WebSocket

**What it is**: Full-duplex TCP-based protocol with its own handshake (protocol upgrade from HTTP).

**Use cases**: Chat, collaborative editing, gaming, any bidirectional real-time communication.

**Pros**:
- Bidirectional real-time communication
- Binary data support
- Lower latency for high-frequency updates
- No HTTP overhead once connected

**Cons**:
- More complex setup (protocol upgrade, connection management)
- Requires WebSocket-aware server infrastructure
- Harder to debug than HTTP
- Overkill for one-way notifications

**Sources**:
- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebSocket
- https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6455

### Browser Support

- **SSE**: All modern browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge). IE doesn't support, but IE is deprecated.
- **WebSocket**: Universal modern browser support.

Both are safe for our target users (modern browsers).

### Implementation Complexity

**SSE**:
- Client: EventSource API (built-in, ~10 lines of code)
- Server: Standard HTTP endpoint that keeps connection open and sends events
- Simpler to set up and debug

**WebSocket**:
- Client: WebSocket API (more code for connection management, reconnect logic)
- Server: WebSocket server (more infrastructure, different from standard HTTP)
- More moving parts

## Limitations / Gaps

- Didn't research specific library ecosystem (focused on protocol comparison)
- Didn't analyze load/scalability implications (would need infrastructure details)
- Didn't test actual implementation (theoretical comparison only)

## Recommendations

**For dashboard notifications (one-way server→client updates)**:

✅ **Use SSE** - simpler, sufficient for use case, easier to maintain.

**Consider WebSocket only if**:
- Requirements change to include user→server real-time streaming
- Need bidirectional features (collaborative editing, chat, etc.)
- Need binary data streaming

For current requirements (dashboard notifications), SSE is the right choice.

## Open Questions

- What server-side SSE library works best with our stack? (Node.js? Go?)
- How many concurrent SSE connections do we expect? (affects infrastructure planning)
- Do we need message queuing for offline users?
- Should we implement notification batching or stream immediately?

(These questions may warrant follow-up research or architectural decisions)
```

